[[File:Bach-clefguide.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.35|This is the explanation of clefs which begins the Wilhelm Friedemann ''KlavierbÃ¼chlein'', in Johann Sebastian's hand.]] '''''KlavierbÃ¼chlein fÃ¼r Wilhelm Friedemann Bach''''' (Bach's original spelling: ''Clavier-BÃ¼chlein vor Wilhelm Friedemann Bach'') is a collection of [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]] music compiled by the [[Germany|German]] [[Baroque]] [[composer]] [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] for his eldest son [[Wilhelm Friedemann Bach|Wilhelm Friedemann]]. It is frequently referred to simply as ''KlavierbÃ¼chlein''.
Johann Sebastian began compiling the collection in 1720. Most of the pieces included are better known as parts of the [[Well-Tempered Clavier]] and the [[Inventions and Sinfonias]]. The authorship of most other works is debated: particularly the famous Little Preludes [[BWV]] 924â932 are sometimes attributed to Wilhelm Friedemann Bach.
== Contents == [[File:Bach-ornamentguide.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.35|A guide to ornaments, written in Bach's hand and included in the ''KlavierbÃ¼chlein fÃ¼r Wilhelm Friedemann Bach''.]] [[File:Bach-applicatio-autograph.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.35|Close-up of the first bar of Applicatio in C major, BWV 994. Bach's fingering marks are clearly visible.]] {{Listen | image = [[File:Video Camera Icon.png|50px]] | help = | filename = Bach PrÃ©lude en rÃ© mineur BWV 926.ogg | alt = Audiovideo of Bach Prelude in D minor for harpsichord, BWV 926 (1:20) | title = Prelude in D minor for harpsichord, BWV 926 (1:20) | description = No. 4, Prelude in D minor, played on harpsichord }} {{Listen | filename = Johann Sebastian Bach - book i- prelude and fugue no. 8 in e flat minor, bwv 853 - prelude.ogg | title = BWV 853/1 Prelude in E-flat minor | description = KlavierbÃ¼chlein fÃ¼r Wilhelm Friedemann Bach No. 23, Praeludium [No. 10] is an incomplete copy (35 bars), partly in the handwriting of W. F. Bach and partly in the handwriting of J. S. Bach, of the Prelude of ''[[The Well-Tempered Clavier]]'' book I, No. 8 (BWV 853) | pos = }} The book begins with a [[preface]] that contains an explanation of [[clef]]s and a guide to playing [[Ornament (music)|ornaments]]. The pieces of the collection are arranged by complexity, beginning with the most simple works. Of these, [[Applicatio]] in C major BWV 994 and Prelude in G minor BWV 930 are particularly notable because they are the only surviving works that feature the [[Fingering (music)|fingering]] in Bach's own hand (the only other Bach piece with fingering marks is the C major Prelude BWV 870a, however, the marks are not in Bach's hand. They were probably added by [[Johann Caspar Vogler]], Bach's pupil and successor at [[Weimar]]<ref>Faulkner, 13.</ref>).
