{{Use DMY dates|date=October 2017}} {{Vietnamese name|[[Pháº¡m]]|NguyÃªn}} {{Infobox person | name = Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn | other_names = NgÃ¢n XuyÃªn (pen name) | image = File:NhÃ lÃ½ luáº­n phÃª bÃ¬nh vÄn há»c Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn.jpg | caption = NguyÃªn speaking at an event held by the Center for East-West Cultures and Languages ''(Trung tÃ¢m vÄn hoÃ¡ ngÃ´n ngá»¯ ÄÃ´ng TÃ¢y)'', 4 December 2008 | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|5|15|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Nghá» An Province]] | nationality = [[Vietnam]]ese | occupation = Writer and [[literary translator]] | known_for = Vietnamese translations of the works of [[Georges Bataille]], [[Paulo Coelho]], [[Jhumpa Lahiri]], [[Milan Kundera]], [[Haruki Murakami]], and others }}
'''Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn''' (born 15 May 1958), better known by his [[pen name]] '''NgÃ¢n XuyÃªn''', is a [[Vietnamese literature|Vietnamese writer]] and [[literary translation|literary translator]].<ref name="TN20100329">{{cite news|url=http://www.thanhnien.com.vn/van-hoa-nghe-thuat/chang-emxi-chuyen-dan-dat-cac-so-van-chuong-328294.html|author=Nguyá» n Viá»t Chiáº¿n|title=ChÃ ng 'em-xi' chuyÃªn dáº«n dáº¯t cÃ¡c 'sÃ´' vÄn chÆ°Æ¡ng|work=[[Thanh NiÃªn]]|date=29 March 2010|accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref>
==Personal life and career== Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn was born in [[Nghá» An Province]].<ref name="TN20100329"/> He did his early education in neighbouring [[HÃ TÄ©nh Province]], where in grade 6 and again in grade 10 he won district and provincial awards for writing.<ref name="NDT20121227">{{cite news|url=http://www.nguoiduatin.vn/chuyen-ve-nha-phe-binh-dat-so-nhat-viet-nam-a59127.html|author=Thanh XuÃ¢n|title=Chuyá»n vá» nhÃ phÃª bÃ¬nh 'Äáº¯t sÃ´' nháº¥t Viá»t Nam|work=NgÆ°á»i ÄÆ°a tin|date=27 December 2012|accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref> He studied [[Russian language|Russian]] as his foreign language in high school, and continued learning it as a student in the literature department of the [[University of Hanoi]] (''[[:vi:TrÆ°á»ng Äáº¡i há»c Tá»ng há»£p HÃ Ná»i|TrÆ°á»ng Äáº¡i há»c Tá»ng há»£p HÃ Ná»i]]'', now part of the [[Vietnam National University, Hanoi]]).<ref name="ANTGCT20131205">{{cite news|url=http://antgct.cand.com.vn/Chuyen-de/Nguyen-van-la-Nguyen-315599/|title= NhÃ phÃª bÃ¬nh vÄn há»c Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn, Chá»§ tá»ch Há»i NhÃ vÄn HÃ Ná»i: 'NguyÃªn váº«n lÃ NguyÃªn'|work=An ninh tháº¿ giá»i Cuá»i thÃ¡ng|date=5 December 2013|accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref> He interrupted his university studies to serve in the [[People's Army of Vietnam]] from 1978 to 1982, and was stationed in [[Ho Chi Minh City]]. During that period, he began teaching himself [[French language|French]], and had his first translations of [[French poetry]] published in the newspaper ''[[Tiá»n Phong (newspaper)|Tiá»n Phong]]''.<ref name="NDT20121227"/> He went on to become chairman of the Hanoi Writers' Association ''(Há»i NhÃ vÄn HÃ Ná»i)''.<ref name="ANTGCT20131205"/>
==Works== Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn speaks Russian, French, and English, and has translated works from all of those languages into Vietnamese.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thanhnien.com.vn/van-hoa-nghe-thuat/pham-xuan-nguyen-lam-gi-cung-phai-co-trach-nhiem-va-chat-luong-cao-nhat-co-the-20596.html|author=NgÃ´ Thá» Kim CÃºc|title=Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn: LÃ m gÃ¬ cÅ©ng pháº£i cÃ³ trÃ¡ch nhiá»m vÃ cháº¥t lÆ°á»£ng cao nháº¥t cÃ³ thá»|work=[[Thanh NiÃªn]]|date=30 July 2013|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> He was first exposed to the works of [[Milan Kundera]] in their Russian translations in the [[Union of Russian Writers]] journal ''Foreign Literature'' (Â«[[:ru:ÐÐ½Ð¾ÑÑÑÐ°Ð½Ð½Ð°Ñ Ð»Ð¸ÑÐµÑÐ°ÑÑÑÐ°|ÐÐ½Ð¾ÑÑÑÐ°Ð½Ð½Ð°Ñ Ð»Ð¸ÑÐµÑÐ°ÑÑÑÐ°]]Â»), and himself translated ''[[Immortality (novel)|Immortality]]'' (which was originally in [[Czech language|Czech]]) into Vietnamese from the Russian version.<ref name="ANTGCT20131205"/>
After he spent more than thirty years translating the works of others under his pen name, his first book of his own under his real name, ''NhÃ vÄn nhÆ° Thá» Ná»'' (meaning "A Writer like Thá» Ná»"), was published in 2014.<ref name="VNExpress">{{cite news|url=http://giaitri.vnexpress.net/tin-tuc/sach/lang-van/bien-tap-vien-doa-dot-nha-de-co-ban-thao-cua-pham-xuan-nguyen-3008642.html|title=BiÃªn táº­p viÃªn dá»a Äá»t nhÃ Äá» cÃ³ báº£n tháº£o cá»§a Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn|trans-title=Editor threatened to commit arson to get Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn's draft|work=VNExpress|date=25 June 2014|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> The title is a reference to the character Thá» Ná» in [[Nam Cao]]'s 1941 short story ''[[ChÃ­ PhÃ¨o]]'', a woman who is well known for her unattractive appearance.<ref name="DSPL20140731">{{cite news|url=http://www.doisongphapluat.com/giai-tri/nghe-ga-dau-bac-pham-xuan-nguyen-ke-toi-thi-no-a43698.html|author=Láº¡c ThÃ nh|title=Nghe 'gÃ£ Äáº§u báº¡c' Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn 'ká» tá»i'... Thá» Ná»|trans-title=Hear 'the white-haired man' Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn 'tell all' ... Thá» Ná»|work=BÃ¡o Äá»i Sá»ng PhÃ¡p Luáº­t|date=31 July 2014|accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref> ''NhÃ vÄn nhÆ° Thá» Ná»'' is a collection of essays of [[literary criticism]], discussing fifty-one Vietnamese writers including [[Nam TrÃ¢n]], [[Tháº¿ Lá»¯]], [[Háº£i Triá»u]], [[HoÃ i Thanh]], [[Nguyá» n TuÃ¢n]], [[TrÆ°Æ¡ng Tá»­u]], [[BÃ­ch KhÃª]], [[XuÃ¢n Diá»u]], [[Tá» Há»¯u]], [[Nguyá» n Huy TÆ°á»ng]], [[Nguyá» n Há»¯u Äang]], [[HoÃ ng Cáº§m (poet)|HoÃ ng Cáº§m]], [[Tráº§n Dáº§n]], [[LÃª Äáº¡t]], [[PhÃ¹ng QuÃ¡n]], [[BÃ¹i Ngá»c Táº¥n]], [[Nguyá» n XuÃ¢n KhÃ¡nh]], [[DÆ°Æ¡ng TÆ°á»ng]], [[Báº£o Ninh]], [[Nguyá» n Quang Láº­p]], and [[Vi ThÃ¹y Linh]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://vanhien.vn/vi/news/sach/Nha-phe-binh-Pham-Xuan-Nguyen-Nha-van-nhu-Thi-No-6672/|author=VÅ© Gia HÃ |title=NhÃ phÃª bÃ¬nh Pháº¡m XuÃ¢n NguyÃªn: NhÃ vÄn nhÆ° Thá» Ná»|trans-title=Critic Pháº¡m XuÃ